title: February 21
description:
The Moses family traveled to Louisiana for a visit filled with good people, good times and good food.

After extensive research, we are proud to announce the best places to get a bowl of gumbo in the entire state of Louisiana:

  1. The kitchen of Caroline and Pat Derouen (gold medal winner)
  2. George's, under the I-10 overpass
  3. Louie's, right off the LSU campus

children.title: Snow!
children.description:
Louisiana evokes many things for us: pelicans, stately oaks bearded with spanish moss, turtles sunning on logs.

Snow was pretty far from our minds when we were packing our luggage with sandals and tank tops. But that is, in fact, what we got on our first morning.

children.title: Campus
children.description:
We had planned to stroll around the LSU campus but cut it short because of the cold.

We did buy an LSU jacket and thick LSU socks, which helped us look like natives rather than the incense-burning tree-hugging eco-hippies we are.

children.title: LSU
children.description:
There was only a 1/2 inch of snow on the ground but everyone was very excited because it NEVER snows in Louisiana. It snowed 2 or 3 times in Dean's childhood.

We saw many miniature snowmen and some fancy LSU snow letters near Mike the Tiger's cage. Mike is the LSU mascot. We envied Mike his fur coat.

children.title: Homecoming
children.description:
The house where Dean grew up hadn't changed one iota.

The neighbor kids were having a snowball fight. They were home because the school district declared a snow day.

children.title: U High
children.description:
Dean and Lucie met 20 years ago at University Lab School, a.k.a. U High. Because it was a snow day there was no one to say hello to.

Hi Mr. Delacroix!

Picture taken by an 8 year old photographer.

Photo by Felix Moses

children.title: Hannah
children.description:
Since schools closed for the snow, we were able to visit and catch up with cousin Zach (who is a math teacher) and meet his wife Dawn and their kids Hannah (9) and Isabelle (2).

Hannah approved of Dean's style of play.

children.title: Wrestle 1
children.description: Why is Milo's butt sprouting from Hannah's back?

children.title: Wrestle 2
children.description:
Little Isabelle wasn't used to such play. She partook gingerly in a bit of the rumble, but mostly fretted that her sister was getting horribly maimed.

She was especially distressed at Hannah's hat getting knocked off her head. Don't worry, Isabelle, it's detachable!

children.title: Cousins
children.description: Even before our first parade, Felix got his hands on the cousins' beads for a taste of Mardi Gras.

children.title: Alex
children.description:
Felix and uncle Alex at George's.

We stayed at Alex's house. He was a very gracious host, even going as far as exiling his two young kittens out into the freezing cold of the storage shed out back.

children.title: Dawn & Zach
children.description:
Zach and Dawn met in Brussels where they both worked in an international school until moving to Baton Rouge last summer.

Dawn, who is British, is still adjusting to life in Louisiana. By next summer we're sure she'll have learned to speak proper English.

children.title: First Beads
children.description:
Milo caught the official first beads of Mardi Gras at the Southdowns parade, a small neighborly affair just a block from Dean's childhood home.

Felix and Milo loved the small parade. In the airport in Texas the kids saw King Sized and Fun Sized candy bars sitting next to each other. This prompted Milo to declare, "I'm Fun Sized!" He certainly is, and so was this parade.

children.title: Bead-o-Rama
children.description:
On the way back to Alex's after our first Mardi Gras parade.

We caught so many beads that Milo lost interest. Instead, Milo decided to specialize in catching doubloons for the rest of our trip.

Doubloons are large coins minted especially for a particular Mardi Gras parade. They are much scarcer than beads and hence more valuable to our treasure hunter.

children.title: Doug
children.description: Dean's childhood best friend Doug made the trip from Texas so we could spend a little time together. It was good to see him and meet his wife and children.

children.title: Dogs
children.description: Felix is walking Doug's new puppy, Jesse.  Doug's son, John (4), is on Grandpa Wendell's shoulders.

children.title: Spanish Town
children.description:
The Spanish Town parade is a Baton Rouge institution.

People warned us it would be lewd and rowdy. Those people had obviously never attended any of OUR parties.

children.title: Crowd
children.description: The parade wends its way through a downtown Baton Rouge that is thankfully sunnier and warmer than the previous day.

children.title: Linda
children.description: Papa John and Linda snatched beads with us.

children.title: Pink
children.description: Each float is equipped with hooks laden with many, many, many beads.

children.title: Throw
children.description: Throw me something, Mister!

children.title: Catch
children.description: The usual "throws" are beads, doubloons and plastic cups designed just for that parade.  However, they sometimes chuck other stuff: mini footballs, panties, plastic boobs or (pictured) puzzles.

children.title: Cop
children.description: Enforcing that the good times roll peacefully.

children.title: Tiki Float
children.description: This float saved us from a massive meltdown. Milo had been near tears because it turned out Spanish Town didn't have doubloons made this year.  Each float brought more disappointment to our young treasure hunter. Thankfully, this tiki float threw some tiki coins and saved the day.

children.title: Doubloons
children.description: Felix and Milo danced 'mongst the feet of strangers to harvest precious pavement treasure.

children.title: Lawnmowers
children.description: Spanish Town tradition: the lawnmower brigade.

children.title: Capitol
children.description: A post-parade stroll by the lake of the Baton Rouge capitol is the perfect place to show off your beads.

children.title: Nutria
children.description:
This is a nutria.

Like the Moses family, nutria came to Louisiana from California. It was the 1930's and California was just a waystop from nutria's actual country of origin, Venezuela.

Even though they're sort of cute, Louisiana declared nutria personae non grata because their population exploded to the point they were causing extensive damage to the ecosystem by eating all the marsh vegetation.

The state put a bounty of $5 on every nutria tail and the population's gone down. But they still seem plenty plentiful to us.

children.title: Papa John
children.description: Papa John loves his dog Hannah. He introduced his grandsons to the joy of playing catch with her.

children.title: Yard
children.description: Playing doggie games in Papa John's spacious yard.

children.title: Hannah
children.description: Felix and Milo approved of Hannah.

children.title: Kim's Kids
children.description:
Linda has a daughter named Kim. We had a lovely dinner with Kim and her husband Paul and their children Joshua (11), Catherine (10) and Miriam (6).

We're still trying to figure out the actual term for how we're related. Half-step siblings?

children.title: Pillow Fight
children.description: The kids got along great and had a big pillow fight while the grown-ups discussed the best places to get cajun food.

children.title: USS Kidd
children.description:
We toured the USS Kidd, permanently docked in Baton Rouge.

Once upon a long time ago, Dean spent a night in it with his boy scout troop.

children.title: Sailor Milo
children.description: Sailor Milo operates the heavy artillery.

children.title: Sailor Felix
children.description: Sailor Felix guns down enemies looming on the Mason-Dixon line.

children.title: Sailor Lucie
children.description: Sailor Lucie erupts into a rousing verse of "Proud to Be an American".

children.title: Aunt Pat
children.description: Lunch at Sammy's with Nana, Aunt Pat and Cousin John.

children.title: The Hindles
children.description: Hi, Aunt Pat and Cousin John!

children.title: One More
children.description: One fine lookin' pack of relatives.

children.title: John
children.description: John and Felix.  Felix wore pink beads because it was Valentine's Day.

children.title: Crawfish
children.description:
There was no shortage of reasons to visit Louisiana at this particular time: Mardi Gras, the Saints winning the Super Bowl, a school vacation, cheap flights.

Another powerful lure was crawfish season. Here Lucie attacks her crawfish boil: a heaping mount of crawfish cooked in spicy water with spicy corn and spicy potatoes.

children.title: Crawfish 2
children.description: Milo sampled a crawfish and liked it but then the spices got to him. He complained of tingling lips the rest of the meal and drank many glasses of water.

children.title: Denham Springs
children.description: Uncle Pat, Zach's father, lives on a spread of land in Denham Springs, about 45 minutes out of Baton Rouge.

children.title: Uncle Pat
children.description: Uncle Pat: cajun cowboy and proud of it.

children.title: Trailer
children.description:
Pat's ranch has everything a children's wonderland needs:
  • goats
  • a horse
  • a cow
  • several barns
  • a lake with a canoe
  • lots of mud
  • farm equipment
  • a big trailer
  • heavy chains and other miscellaneous semi-dangerous objects

children.title: Chains
children.description: We are hazy on the details of the game that Felix and Hannah cooked up. The important part is that Milo was consenting.

children.title: Lucky
children.description:
This is Lucky the cow.

He's named "Lucky" because he's lucky to be alive. His mom abandoned him at birth, but Pat's wife Caroline took pity and raised him on a bottle.

children.title: Goat
children.description: Lucie and a little goat.

children.title: Pet
children.description:
Zach and family go to Pat's almost every weekend.

We would too, if we had a grandpa with a ranch living nearby!

children.title: Who Dat
children.description:
Pat has a side business doing metal work. He created some awesome WHO DAT pieces in celebration of the Saint's historic Super Bowl win.

The Saints is New Orleans' and Louisiana's football team. They had never gone to the Super Bowl before. Their win was as big to people here as, oh, perhaps the Apollo Moon Landings.

children.title: Who Dat 2
children.description:
Pat generously gave us one of his WHO DAT pieces to take home to California with us.

We were honored!

children.title: Ferry
children.description:
Going to Houma for a swamp tour.

We crossed the mighty Mississippi on the Plaquemine ferry.

children.title: Ferry 2
children.description: Uncle Alex, Linda and Papa John joined us on our swamp expedition.

children.title: Caution
children.description:
We saw no alligators (they are hibernating this time of year) but DID eat fried alligator.

Yes, it tastes like chicken.

children.title: On de Boat
children.description: All bundled up on the swamp boat... it was a cold cold day.

children.title: De Boat 2
children.description: I think Dean slept in his LSU jacket.

children.title: Swamp
children.description: Milo couldn't understand the appeal of an alligator-less swamp, but the rest of us enjoyed the scenery.

children.title: Swamp 2
children.description: Cypress trees, spanish moss and brackish water, oh my!

children.title: Swamp 3
children.description:
The green plant on the surface is water hyacinth, an invasive plant accidentally introduced during the 1884 Cotton Exposition held in New Orleans, when the Japanese delegation distributed several plants imported from Venezuela.

It's one of the world's fastest growing plants, forming thick mats that choke the oxygen from the water. Louisiana has unsuccessfully tried to get rid of it ever since.

They even tried introducing nutria into the wild to stop it. That didn't work out so well.

children.title: Swamp 4
children.description: The "knees" poking out are part of the root system of the cypress trees.

children.title: Hat
children.description: Felix really liked Alex's hat, especially after he learned that it was a genuine helmet liner from Alex's days in the Army.

children.title: Lafayette
children.description:
On Fat Tuesday -- Mardi Gras day itself -- we headed to Lafayette for a "down home" Mardi Gras parade.

There were lots of Saints fans and lots of recliners in the backs of pickup trucks.

children.title: Waiting
children.description:
Unlike Southdowns and Spanish Town, Lafayette has barriers to keep people from getting up close.

Milo got a stern warning from a cop after slipping out into the street to collect a handful of precious doubloons. It was worth it!

children.title: King
children.description: The king of Lafayette Mardi Gras.

children.title: Marching Band
children.description: The Lafayette parade featured many high school bands from neighboring towns.

children.title: Tut
children.description:
What with the big floats and the barriers, the beads had to be hurled to the crowd. They were actually rather painful to catch.

The kids quickly learned to duck for cover instead of reaching for them.

children.title: Fence
children.description: Mardi Gras beads and a Saints flag... how 'bout dat yard?

children.title: Who Dat Dr.
children.description: This pretty much sums up the Louisiana experience.

children.title: Geocache
children.description: There's a geocache around here somewhere...

children.title: Dock
children.description: Lucie waits for her boat to come in.

children.title: Watery Land
children.description: Felix didn't realize this was a dock on water and nearly stepped off.

children.title: Airboat
children.description:
Another day, another swamp tour.

This one was RATHER faster than the last.

children.title: Loud
children.description: This swamp tour was rather LOUDER than the last.

children.title: Pause
children.description: Every now and then we took off the headgear and heard a story about the swamps.

children.title: I-10
children.description:
The I-10 interstate runs clear across America, from the Atlantic to the Pacific, crossing the huge Atchafalaya Basin between Baton Rouge and Lafayette.

It's one of the longest bridges in the world.

Dean had never examined the underside.

children.title: Driver
children.description: Monsieur Blanchard, the driver of the airboat, was from a Cajun family, but he didn't speak any French.   In the early-to-mid 1900's the government actively discouraged such things, and a lot of the French language in Louisiana was snuffed out.

children.title: Geocache #1000
children.description:
We introduced Nana to Geocaching about a year ago.

Here, she's finding her 1000th geocache!

That's about three per day. We're wondering if there's a geocaching hall of fame.

children.title: Mardi Cache
children.description: Cache 1000 receives a boatload of Mardi Gras spirit.

children.title: Spaghetti
children.description: Spaghetti and king cake with Zach's lovely family.

children.title: Z + D
children.description: Dean's cuz and his main squeeze share a tender moment.

children.title: The Haul
children.description: After all the parades were finished, we estimated we caught Milo's weight in beads.

children.title: Haul @ Home
children.description:
We made it safely back to Berkeley with our WHO DAT sign, our beads, and a whole pile of good memories.

We DID manage to lose Milo for about a half hour in the Houston airport, but that's another story for another time.
